 Hence, we can write
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mm_{1}=\mm_{0}+\mathbf{U}\mathbf{C}\mathbf{V}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{U}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 columns of identity matrix, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $q\times q$
\end_inset

 matrix and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{V}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 rows of identity matrix.
 Hence, Woodbury matrix identity shows that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mm_{1}^{-1}=(\mm_{0}+\mathbf{U}\mathbf{C}\mathbf{V})^{-1}=\mm_{0}^{-1}-\mm_{0}^{-1}\mathbf{U}(\mathbf{C}^{-1}+\mathbf{V}\mm_{0}^{-1}\mathbf{U})^{-1}\mathbf{V}\mm_{0}^{-1}.
\]

\end_inset

Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mm_{0}^{-1}\mathbf{U}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{V}\mm_{0}^{-1}\mathbf{U}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{V}\mm_{0}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 are just blocks of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mm_{0}^{-1}$
\end_inset

